uge impact on the development of natural religion, moral sense theory, aesthetics, and environmentalism.Combining captivating historical details and flashes of humor, A Philosophy of Beauty not only rediscovers and illuminates a fascinating philosopher but also offers an inspiring reflection about the role beauty can play in our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh  aAdmiration.  aAesthetic Theory.  aAesthetics of nature.  aAesthetics.  aAffection.  aArt for art's sake.  aAtheism.  aAuthor.  aBelief in God.  aCertainty.  aConcept.  aConformity.  aConsideration.  aContingency (philosophy).  aCourtesy.  aCriticism.  aDeclaration of love.  aDeity.  aDeontological ethics.  aDivine providence.  aEfficacy.  aElegance.  aEloquence.  aEmotion.  aEmpathy.  aEnthusiasm.  aEnvironmental philosophy.  aEpistemology.  aEssay.  aEstimation.  aEthics.  aEtiquette.  aExcellence.  aExplanation.  aExtrapolation.  aEyesore.  aFeeling.  aFine art.  aFormal garden.  aGod.  aGood and evil.  aGratitude.  aGreatness.  aHistory painting.  aHolism.  aHuman.  aHumility.  aIncentive.  aIndividual.  aIndulgence.  aInnuendo.  aInstrumental value.  aIntention.  aIrony.  aKowtow.  aLightness.  aLoyalty.  aMoral agency.  aMoral character.  aMorality and religion.  aMorality.  aNoun adjunct.  aObedience (human behavior).  aOf Miracles.  aOn Liberty.  aOn Virtue.  aOriginality.  aPainting.  aParody.  aPersuasion.  aPhenomenon.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPiety.  aPoliteness.  aRationality.  aReason.  aReligion.  aReputation.  aResult.  aRighteousness.  aSelf-esteem.  aSelfishness.  aSimplicity.  aSincerity.  aSoliloquy.  aState of nature.  aSto